text.value: The African Seed Access Index (TASAI) is a seed industry program of TASAI Inc. TASAI monitors the development and competitiveness of national seed sectors in Africa. The central objective of TASAI is to encourage African governments and (international) development agencies to foster enabling environments that will accelerate the development of local, private sector-led seed systems serving smallholder farmers.dex (TASAI) is a seed industry program of TASAI Inc. TASAI monitors the development and competitiveness of national seed sectors in Africa. The central objective of TASAI is to encourage African governments and (international) development agencies to foster enabling environments that will accelerate the development of local, private sector-led seed systems serving smallholder farmers.

The index covers 21 indicators that are divided into the five broad categories: Research and Development, Industry Competitiveness, Service to Smallholder Farmers, Policy and Regulations, and Institutional Support. TASAI’s intended outcome is improved access to locally adapted, affordable, and high-quality seeds of appropriate varieties by smallholder farmers in Sub-Saharan Africa.

TASAI is intended for use by practitioners in the public and private sectors and development aid agencies to both inform and compel change within a country’s seed sector. This is accomplished through collaboration with ongoing seed sector development efforts to improve the performance of seed systems. For more information on TASAI, please visit us at [www.tasai.org](http://www.tasai.org).
Guidelines for Survey: Please take note of the following information to guide your responses.
A) **- Government seed agency:** This survey is targeting the government agency/ department mandated to handle seed industry issues in the country.

B) **- Crop selection:** This survey is part of an evaluation of the performance of the formal seed sector in Malawi with a focus on the following key food security crops: maize, bean, groundnut, and soya bean.
C) **- Certified seed:** The survey seeks information pertaining to certified seed.

D) **- Opinion questions:** Throughout the questionnaire, we use a 10-point scale to gauge respondents’ satisfaction rating about various seed-sector related issues, and we use a 5-point scale to evaluate respondent’s extent of (dis)agreement.
For questions/clarifications about this survey, please contact: Mainza Mugoya, Program Coordinator, The African Seed Access Index (TASAI) E-mail: mmugoya@tasai.org. Tel: +254731671465

Request for supporting documentation on the FISP program.

8) Evaluate the following aspects of the FISP
Using your experience as the basis, rate the following statements about the seed subsidy program in 2019
8.1) “In 2019, the seed procurement process through FISP was open and transparent.” (i.e., The bidder with the best service/product was awarded the contract.)

8.2) “In 2019, the seed procurement process through FISP was predictable.” (i.e., seed companies were provided with sufficient information and advance notice about the types and quantities of seed to be procured to inform their production plan.)
8.3) “In 2019, the FISP payment process was efficient.” (i.e., seed companies got paid on time.)

14) Status of institutional arrangements for sector coordination
This question asks about the key institutions, their mandates, capacities and the coordination arrangements within the seed sector.
14.1) Legal status of seed sector coordination
Do laws/regulations establish/define the key institution(s) responsible for seed sector coordination?

Do the legal instruments (laws/ regulations/ ordinances) define the institutional arrangements for seed sector coordination? (E.g., is there an overseeing committee/ board/ council that brings together different seed sector stakeholders with the purpose of sector coordination/oversight?)
Does the oversight committee/ board/ council, provided for in the legal instrument(s), meet on a regular basis?
If yes, how many times were such meetings convened in **2019**?
If yes, is the private sector an active participant in these meetings?
14.2) Functions of the coordinator vs other public institutions:
14.2.1) Are the following key seed sector functions defined in the legal instruments? Mark all that apply.
Legal instruments include all relevant policy and legislative instruments that exist in the country, such as the Seed Act/Regulations, Plant Variety Protection Act/Regulations and the Seed Policy
14.2.2) Do the legal instruments designate a specific institution responsible for these functions?
If no, describe any duplication of functions among the various institutions in charge of coordination.
Briefly describe the human resource capacity of the institution responsible for seed sector coordination

The question asks whether the institution's human resource capacity is adequate in terms of numbers and skills in the managerial and technical positions; if not, what are the areas inadequacy? The responses are subjective but useful nevertheless
Briefly describe the financial capacity of the institution responsible for seed sector coordination

The question asks about the institution's financial capacity. Responses may mention (i) if the organization regularly faces significant budget shortfalls (i.e. big difference between planned vs actual budget), and (ii) the various sources of funding, e.g. government, service fees, donors, etc.
Is there a framework/system for coordination (including reporting) of seed-sector actions within the parent ministry?

Is there coordination between the seed regulatory agency/seed unit and the parent ministry in the design, implementation and/or monitoring of government agricultural programs that have a seed sector component (e.g. agricultural input subsidy programs, agricultural extension programs)?
If yes, describe these coordination arrangements.

Is there coordination between the government agencies and the private sector in the design, implementation, and/or monitoring of government agricultural programs that have a seed sector component (e.g., agricultural input subsidy programs, agricultural extension programs)?
If yes, describe these coordination arrangements
15.1) What were the key opportunities for the formal seed sector in 2020?
15.2) What were the key challenges for the formal seed sector in 2020?
16) Any additional comments regarding the seed sector in your country?
### Thank you for your thoughtful responses.
